            {
                "s2_paper_id": "077725763912393a920b67e5c1811c5246fed109",
                "title": "Scintillation and High-Rate TEC Observations at Mid Latitudes During the Gannon Storm",
                "year": 2025,
                "venue": "United States National Committee of URSI National Radio Science Meeting",
                "citation_count": 0,
                "reference_count": 8,
                "abstract": "We present scintillation and ionospheric total electron content (TEC) measurements made by a network of low-cost GNSS based monitors distributed over North and Central America during the May 2024 super geomagnetic storm. The observations show severe TEC gradients and fluctuations occurring over the US that persisted for several hours between May 10 18:00 UT and May 11 12:00 UT TEC fluctuations were quantified using the rate of change of TEC index (ROTI). Amplitude scintillation was quantified using the 1-minute S4 index. Despite severe TEC perturbations, only weak to moderate amplitude scintillation events were observed. Additionally, the observations show that while ROTI increases persisted during several hours, S4 increases were observed for only a few minutes.",
